[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The next AI coding skill is not writing the perfect prompt. It is building the loop that prompts the agent for you. This idea is called loop craft. Peter Steinberger put it bluntly. You should not be prompting coding agents anymore.'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You should be designing loops that prompt your agents. And that sounds abstract until you see what Karpathy built. Karpathy\'s auto research repo gives an agent one job, improve a small language model training setup.'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The agent edits train.py, runs a fixed 5-minute experiment, checks the validation score, keeps the change if it improved, discards it if it got worse, and repeats.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is the difference. A prompt asks once. A loop asks, checks reality, remembers the result, and tries again. There are levels to this. At the bottom, the model samples tokens until it hits a'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stop condition. One level up, an agent calls tools until there are no more tool calls. Above that, a goal loop runs the agent, judges the result, and retries.'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Above that, a meta loop spawns agents, reviews them, and responds better attempts. And at the top, a team loop allocates work across many agents. Loopcraft is the skill of deciding what'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'repeats, what counts as progress, who judges it, and when the system must stop. This is already showing up in the products. OpenAI defines a Codex automation as a scheduled or recurring Codex task.'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Anthropic describes agents as language models using tools based on environmental feedback in a loop. And Anthropic\'s own multi-agent research system uses a primary agent that breaks a query into subtasks and sends'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subagents to work in parallel. In their internal research evil, that multi-agent setup outperformed a single-agent Claude Opus 4 setup by 90.2%.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But this is where most people get it wrong. More loops do not automatically mean better results. Anthropic says agents can use about four times more tokens than normal chats, and multi-agent systems can use about 15'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times more. They also warn that many coding tasks are not as parallelizable as research tasks. So, before you build any loop, run one test. A loop only earns its cost under four'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conditions. The task has to repeat, so the setup pays off across many runs. Verification has to be automated, so something can fail the work without you in the room. Your token budget has to absorb the'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'waste, because loops reprocess context, retry, and explore. And the agent needs a senior engineer\'s tools. Logs, a way to run the code and see what breaks. Miss one condition and a single good'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt still wins. The honest version is loop engineering is real, and most developers do not need it yet. If you pass that test, build the smallest loop that works. Four parts, no swarm.'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One automation that fires on a schedule and stops on a clear condition. One skill, so the agent stops re-deriving your project from zero every run. One state file, so tomorrow\'s run resumes instead of restarting.'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And one gate, the test, type check, or build that fails bad work automatically. That gate is the part that decides whether the loop helps or just spends. And the metric that matters is not'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokens. It is cost per accepted change. If you are then half your loop\'s changes get accepted, you are back doing the review work the loop was supposed to remove. Skip the gate and you get what one'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engineer named the Ralph Wiggum loop. The agent signals it is done before it actually is. The loop exits on a half-finished job, and with no hard stop, it just keeps spending. That is why the internet is split on'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. One camp says loops are the real coding interface. The other says it is a tax that only makes sense with unlimited tokens. Both are right, depending on whether you built a gate or not.'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, the takeaway is not stop thinking and let agents do everything. The takeaway is stop being the next button. Your job moves up a level. You define the objective. You define the proof.'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You define the boundary. Build the loop and stay the engineer. So, which side are you on? Are loops the real coding interface? Or a token tax that only pays off with an unlimited plan?'

[04:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Tell me in the comments and subscribe for more honest, hands-on artificial intelligence engineering.'
